  "opening_engine": {
    "purpose": "This is the system that governs how the post opens and how every section opens. It is derived from eight master writing principles and translated into executable techniques. The agent MUST apply these techniques — not interpret them philosophically, but use them as a toolkit when writing any opening: post introduction, H2 section, or conclusion.",
    "master_principles": {
      "note": "These are the source principles. The techniques below are how to execute them.",
      "1_voice": "Average writers sound like they are trying to write well. Great writers sound like themselves — and that self is interesting. Voice is not vocabulary. It is the angle, the claim, the thing no one else would have said.",
      "2_specificity": "The specific unlocks the universal because it feels true, it feels lived. 'She was nervous' is telling. 'She wiped her palms on her trousers three times before knocking' is showing. The specific detail does more emotional work than any adjective ever could.",
      "3_unexpected_emotion": "Emotions are most effectively evoked when the reader is not expecting to be moved. The reader does not see it coming. They just find themselves nodding, or invested, or moved — and they do not know why.",
      "4_ruthless_cutting": "Fewer crap bits. Every sentence that does not earn its place kills the ones around it. Great writers cut. Average writers add.",
      "5_observation": "The observation that feels obvious in hindsight — 'why did I not think of that?' — is the mark of a great writer. They noticed it. The reader did not.",
      "6_connection_over_impression": "The goal is not to impress with vocabulary, complexity, or beautiful prose. The goal is: does the reader feel this was written for them?",
      "7_haunt_not_divert": "Good writing is diverting while great writing is haunting. For Mirellé: you cannot achieve 'haunting' in a nail blog post. But you can achieve the version of it — a post the reader remembers, quotes to a friend, bookmarks, returns to.",
      "8_read_ruthlessly": "The gap between what you intended and what the reader experiences is where bad writing lives. Read what you actually wrote, not what you meant to write."
    },
    "opening_techniques": {
      "rule": "Every post introduction and every H2 section must open using one of these seven techniques. No two consecutive sections may use the same technique. Track which technique is used per section and rotate deliberately. Technique assignment is done in pre_write_planning_phase step8 — not decided during writing.",
      "technique_1_claim": {
        "name": "The Claim",
        "principle": "Voice",
        "what": "Open with a direct, opinionated statement — a position the editor holds, not a setup for information",
        "nail_blog_example": "A sheer pink nail is not a safe choice. It is the hardest choice to get right.",
        "why_it_works": "Sets a POV immediately. The reader either agrees and leans in, or disagrees and leans in. Either way, they are in.",
        "avoid": "Do not make claims that are obviously true or expected. The claim must surprise slightly."
      },
      "technique_2_specific_detail": {
        "name": "The Specific Detail",
        "principle": "Specificity",
        "what": "Open with a concrete, specific observation — a number, a material, a behaviour, a texture — before any general statement",
        "nail_blog_example": "Three coats. That is the exact point where a jelly polish stops being translucent and starts being a finish.",
        "why_it_works": "Specificity signals that the writer has actually been here. It builds trust in the first sentence.",
        "avoid": "Do not open with a general category and then add a specific. Lead with the specific."
      },
      "technique_3_reframe": {
        "name": "The Reframe",
        "principle": "Observation",
        "what": "Open by showing the reader something they thought they already understood — then shift it",
        "nail_blog_example": "Most people avoid negative space nail art because it looks complicated. It is actually the most forgiving finish to apply.",
        "why_it_works": "Creates an immediate 'wait, really?' moment. The reader's assumption is disrupted — they have to keep reading to understand why.",
        "avoid": "The reframe must be true, not just contrarian. It must hold up under scrutiny."
      },
      "technique_4_tension": {
        "name": "The Tension",
        "principle": "Unexpected emotion",
        "what": "Open by naming a contradiction, a frustration, or a gap between what the reader wants and what usually happens",
        "nail_blog_example": "Cat eye polish looks incredible on every tutorial you have ever watched. On your actual nails, it has never looked like that.",
        "why_it_works": "The reader feels seen. That feeling of recognition is the most effective hook in editorial writing.",
        "avoid": "Do not manufacture tension. It must reflect a real frustration from the audience_intelligence data."
      },
      "technique_5_observation": {
        "name": "The Observation",
        "principle": "See what others miss",
        "what": "Open with a small, precise observation that feels obvious once you have read it — but was not obvious before",
        "nail_blog_example": "The magnet is not the hard part. The timing is.",
        "why_it_works": "The reader thinks: I know about magnets. Then they read the second sentence and realise they did not know the important thing.",
        "avoid": "The observation must be genuinely insightful. A common observation dressed up as insight is the most detectable AI move."
      },
      "technique_6_for_the_reader": {
        "name": "For the Reader",
        "principle": "Connection over impression",
        "what": "Open in a way that makes the reader feel immediately addressed — their situation, their question, their moment",
        "nail_blog_example": "If your gel polish is lifting at the edges within a week, it is not your fault — and it is not the product.",
        "why_it_works": "The reader's problem becomes the first sentence. They feel found rather than marketed to.",
        "avoid": "Do not address the reader with 'you' as a shortcut. The technique is about situational recognition, not pronoun use."
      },
      "technique_7_earned_fragment": {
        "name": "The Earned Fragment",
        "principle": "Ruthless cutting",
        "what": "Open with a single short sentence or fragment that earns its place by landing with weight — then follow with context",
        "nail_blog_example": "Nail prep is not optional. Every finish, every formula, every trend comes down to what happened in the first three minutes.",
        "why_it_works": "The fragment lands like a fact. The second sentence earns the right to expand on it. Nothing was added that did not need to be there.",
        "avoid": "The fragment must have actual weight. A fragment that is just a short sentence without a point is not an earned fragment."
      }
    },
    "application_rules": {
      "post_introduction": [
        "The first sentence of the post must use one of the seven techniques — no exceptions",
        "The first sentence must not be a setup, a context-builder, or an explanation of what is about to happen",
        "After the opening technique is applied, the introduction follows: primary keyword 2 times in first 100 words, immediate value, reader benefit",
        "The opening technique is how you begin — the SEO requirements are how you continue"
      ],
      "h2_section_openings": [
        "Every H2 section must open with one of the seven techniques",
        "No two consecutive sections may use the same technique — rotation is mandatory",
        "Technique assignment is locked in pre_write_planning_phase step8 — execute it, do not re-decide during writing",
        "The choice of technique should be driven by what the section content calls for — not random rotation"
      ],
      "conclusion_opening": [
        "The conclusion must open with either Technique 1 (The Claim) or Technique 3 (The Reframe)",
        "The conclusion is the final editorial statement — it must feel like an editor's last word, not a summary",
        "Never open the conclusion with a backward-looking sentence ('In this post, we covered...')"
      ]
    },
    "banned_opening_approaches": [
      "Restating the H2 heading as a sentence — this is the single most obvious AI writing pattern",
      "Opening with context or setup before the hook — the hook is first, always",
      "Opening with a universal truth that is obviously true ('Everyone wants beautiful nails')",
      "Opening with a question that the section will answer — this is a structural cliche",
      "Opening with a transition from the previous section ('Now that we have covered X, let us look at Y')",
      "Opening with 'When it comes to...'",
      "Opening with 'One of the most...'",
      "Opening with 'In today's world...'",
      "Opening with 'If you're looking for...'",
      "Opening with 'There's no denying that...'",
      "Opening with 'It's no secret that...'",
      "Opening with 'The good news is...'",
      "Opening with 'Here's the thing:'",
      "Opening with 'At the end of the day...'",
      "Opening with 'Whether you're a beginner or a pro...'"
    ]
  },

